sfpsCPResourcesTable.name: sfpsCPResourcesTable
sfpsCPResourcesTable.description: This table contains all Call Processors registered with the CPResources Table and is indexed by the Call Processor id.

sfpsCPResourcesTableEntry.name: sfpsCPResourcesTableEntry
sfpsCPResourcesTableEntry.description: Each entry contains information pertaining to a Call Processor.

sfpsCPResourcesTableId.name: sfpsCPResourcesTableId
sfpsCPResourcesTableId.description: Call Processor id used to index into the table.

sfpsCPResourcesTableName.name: sfpsCPResourcesTableName

sfpsCPResourcesTableAdminStatus.name: sfpsCPResourcesTableAdminStatus
sfpsCPResourcesTableAdminStatus.description: This value represents the current administration status of the associated Call Processor. When enabled(3) the Call Processor is still allowed to call process packets. When this value is disabled(2) the call processor will not process any packets.

sfpsCPResourcesTableStateTime.name: sfpsCPResourcesTableStateTime

sfpsCPResourcesTablePtsIn.name: sfpsCPResourcesTablePtsIn

sfpsCPResourcesTablePtsUsed.name: sfpsCPResourcesTablePtsUsed
sfpsCPResourcesTablePtsUsed.description: The number of packets that have been sent to this Call Processor and accepted for the purpose of processing.

sfpsCPResourcesTablePolicyFlood.name: sfpsCPResourcesTablePolicyFlood
sfpsCPResourcesTablePolicyFlood.description: Number of packets flooded due to Policy.

sfpsCPResourcesResolveFlood.name: sfpsCPResourcesResolveFlood

sfpsCPResourcesConnectOK.name: sfpsCPResourcesConnectOK

sfpsCPResourcesDuplicate.name: sfpsCPResourcesDuplicate

sfpsCPResourcesDiscoverOnly.name: sfpsCPResourcesDiscoverOnly

sfpsCPResourcesDiscoverError.name: sfpsCPResourcesDiscoverError

sfpsCPResourcesResolveFail.name: sfpsCPResourcesResolveFail

sfpsCPResourcesResolveError.name: sfpsCPResourcesResolveError

sfpsCPResourcesPolicyFail.name: sfpsCPResourcesPolicyFail

sfpsCPResourcesPolicyError.name: sfpsCPResourcesPolicyError
sfpsCPResourcesPolicyError.description: Number of packets which caused the Policy to return an error. An error could be caused by a bad packet.

sfpsCPResourcesConnectFail.name: sfpsCPResourcesConnectFail
sfpsCPResourcesConnectFail.description: Number of packets that caused the Connect to fail.

sfpsCPResourcesConnectFlood.name: sfpsCPResourcesConnectFlood
sfpsCPResourcesConnectFlood.description: Number of packets that caused the Connect to flood.

sfpsCPResourcesConnectError.name: sfpsCPResourcesConnectError
sfpsCPResourcesConnectError.description: Number of packets that caused the Connect to return an error.

sfpsCPResourcesConfigTime.name: sfpsCPResourcesConfigTime
sfpsCPResourcesConfigTime.description: Number of time ticks since the last configuration change.

sfpsCPResourcesNeedFlood.name: sfpsCPResourcesNeedFlood

sfpsBlockSourceTable.description: The SourceBlocker table lists all nodes (MAC addresses) that have been heard locally on the switch. Only a certain subset (if any) of the nodes in this table are blocked.

sfpsBlockSourceEntry.description: Entry in the SourceBlocker table indexed by a counter.

sfpsBlockSourceNumCallsShort.description: The number of packets seen from the node during the elapsed time for the short-threshold.

sfpsBlockSourceElapTimeLong.name: sfpsBlockSourceElapTimeLong

sfpsBlockSourceNumCallLong.description: The number of packets seen from the node during the elapsed time for the long-threshold.

sfpsBlockSourceBlockFlag.name: sfpsBlockSourceBlockFlag
sfpsBlockSourceBlockFlag.description: Describes whether the node is blocked or not. There are three possible integer values for this field: 0-notBlocked, 1-Blocked, 2-WouldBeBlocked. The WouldBeBlocked value is used to represent a node that would be in the blocked state if the SourceBlocker was enabled. A node can get into this state only if the blocker is disabled. If the blocker is enabled at this point, the node will be blocked, and a connection filter will be put in place when the next packet is received from this node.

sfpsBlockSourceUnBlockableFlag.name: sfpsBlockSourceUnBlockableFlag
sfpsBlockSourceUnBlockableFlag.description: Flags a node as either Blockable(0) or Unblockable(1). When a node is unblockable, it will never be blocked regardless of the number of packets it sends. The default setting is blockable. Any node can be changed to unblockable via the Source Blocker API (SBAPI).

sfpsBlockSourceFilterPresent.name: sfpsBlockSourceFilterPresent
sfpsBlockSourceFilterPresent.description: Flags whether or not a connection filter is in place for the given node. (This attribute cannot be changed on its own and is therefore used only for diagnostic purposes. It is used internally so that only one filter connection will be mapped per node.)

sfpsBlockSourceNext.name: sfpsBlockSourceNext
sfpsBlockSourceNext.description: If this node entry (instance) is part of a hash chain, the NEXT leaf will contain the index to the next node entry in the chain. Otherwise, it will contain -1.

sfpsBlockSourceBlocksOnlyIndex.name: sfpsBlockSourceBlocksOnlyIndex
sfpsBlockSourceBlocksOnlyIndex.description: Contains the index into the BlockSourceOnly table or the UnblockableOnly table depending on the entry flags. If the 'blocked flag' is set, this value represents the index into the BlockSourceOnly table. If the 'unblockable' flag is set, this value represents the index into the UnblockableOnly table. Otherwise, this value is set to -1 (representing that it is not used.)

sfpsBlockSourceOnlyTable.name: sfpsBlockSourceOnlyTable
sfpsBlockSourceOnlyTable.description: The format of the BlockSourceOnly Table is exactly the same as the SourceBlocker Table. The only difference is that the entries in this table are only a subset of the entries in the SourceBlocker Table. Only the entries that have a BLOCKFLAG set to 'blocked' or 'would-be-blocked' will reside in this table.

sfpsBlockSourceOnlyEntry.description: Entry in the BlockSourceOnly table indexed by a counter.

sfpsBlockSourcePortTable.name: sfpsBlockSourcePortTable
sfpsBlockSourcePortTable.description: The SourceBlock API allows for administratively selecting a port and flagging it as 'unblockable'. The BlockSourcePort table shows which ports are set to 'unblockable' and which ones remain set to the default 'blockable' setting.

sfpsBlockSourcePortPort.name: sfpsBlockSourcePortPort
sfpsBlockSourcePortPort.description: This is the instance part of the table. There will be as many instances as there are logical ports in the device. The attributes represented in subsequent leaves all pertain to this port instance.

sfpsBlockSourcePortBlockability.name: sfpsBlockSourcePortBlockability
sfpsBlockSourcePortBlockability.description: This leaf contains either 0-blockable or 1-unblockable, depending on whether nodes on this port are allowed to be blocked or not.

sfpsBlockSourceAPIVerb.name: sfpsBlockSourceAPIVerb
sfpsBlockSourceAPIVerb.description: Other -- N/A Disable -- disable the source blocker (nodes that are currently blocked will remain blocked, but no additional nodes will be blocked) Enable -- enable the source blocker (allow it to start blocking nodes) ClearAll -- clear the entire block table (this does not remove any connection filters, and should only be used as a diagnostic tool.) BlockMac -- administratively block a node (The node's MAC address must be previously set in the MAC leaf.) UnblockMac -- administratively unblock a node (The node's MAC address must be previously set in the MAC leaf.) SetMacUnblockable -- administratively mark a node as 'unblockable' so that it cannot be blocked. (The node's MAC must be previously set in the MAC leaf.) If the relevant node is blocked at the time the SetMacUnblockable command is issued, the node will automatically be 'unblocked' first. SetMacBlockable -- administratively mark a node as 'blockable' so that it can be blocked. (The node's MAC must be previously set in the MAC leaf.) SetPortUnblockable -- administratively mark a port as 'unblockable' so that any nodes on that port cannot be blocked. (The port number must be previously set in the Port leaf.) SetPortBlockable -- administratively mark a port as 'blockable' so that all nodes on that port can be blocked. (The port number must be previously set in the Port leaf.) SetReapUserCnx -- administratively mark a port as 'blocked' so that administratively mark a port as 'blockable' so that.)

sfpsBlockSourceAPIShortThreshold.name: sfpsBlockSourceAPIShortThreshold

The only limit imposed on this value is that it has to be positive (greater than zero.) There is no upper bound except for what is implied by the size of an integer.
